[[File:Chérubin binocular telescope-CnAM 12811-IMG 6439-white.jpg|thumb|Chérubin's binocular telescope, on display at [[Musée des Arts et Métiers]] in Paris.]]
'''Chérubin d'Orléans''' (1613-1697) was a French scientific instrument maker.

A [[Order of Friars Minor Capuchin|Capucin father]] and distinguished physicist, Chérubin d'Orléans (François Lasséré) devoted himself to the study of [[optics]] and to vision-related problems, which he discussed in ''La dioptrique oculaire and La vision parfaite'' ([[Paris]], 1671 and 1677 respectively). He invented the first [[binocular telescope]]. He devised and may also have built a special type of eyepiece that replaced the lens with a short tube. Chérubin is also credited with producing models of the eyeball for studying the lens function of the [[eye]].

