{{Infobox Galaxy | image = | name = HCM-6A | epoch = [[J2000]] | type = LAE | ra = {{RA|02|39|54.7}} | dec = {{DEC|-01|33|32}} | dist_ly = 12.8 billion light years | z = 6.56 | appmag_v = 24.24 | size = | size_v = | constellation name = [[Cetus]] | notes = | names = HCB2010 J023954-013332 }}
'''HCM-6A''' is an [[Lyman-alpha emitter|LAE]] [[galaxy]] that was found in 2002 by a team led by [[Esther Hu]] from the [[University of Hawaii]], using the [[W. M. Keck Observatory|Keck II Telescope]] in [[Hawaii]]. HCM-6A is located behind the [[Abell 370]] galactic cluster, near [[Messier 77|M77]] <ref>{{cite journal | author=Halton Arp| author2=David Russell| last-author-amp=yes | title=A Possible Relationship between Quasars and Clusters of Galaxies | url=http://www.iop.org/EJ/article/0004-637X/549/2/802/51780.html | journal=The [[Astrophysical Journal]] | volume=549 | issue=2 | pages=802–819 | doi=10.1086/319438 | date=2001 | bibcode=2001ApJ...549..802A }} </ref> in the constellation [[Cetus]], which enabled the astronomers to use Abell 370 as a [[gravitational lens]] to get a clearer image of the object.<ref>{{cite journal | author=E. M. Hu | title=A Redshift z = 6.56 Galaxy behind the Cluster Abell 370 | url=http://www.iop.org/EJ/article/1538-4357/568/2/L75/16083.html | journal=The [[Astrophysical Journal]] Letters | volume=568 | issue=2 | pages=L75–L79 | doi=10.1086/340424 | date=2001 | bibcode=2002ApJ...568L..75H |arxiv = astro-ph/0203091 | name-list-format=vanc | display-authors=1 | last2=Cowie | first2=L. L. | last3=McMahon | first3=R. G. | last4=Capak | first4=P. | last5=Iwamuro | first5=F. | last6=Kneib | first6=J.-P. | last7=Maihara | first7=T. | last8=Motohara | first8=K. }} </ref><ref>[http://www.subarutelescope.org/Pressrelease/2006/09/13/index.html Press release], National Astronomical Observatory of Japan, September 13, 2006</ref>
HCM-6A was the farthest object known at the time of its discovery. It exceeded [[SSA22−HCM1]] (''z'' = 5.74) as the most distant normal galaxy known, and quasar [[SDSSp J103027.10+052455.0]] (''z'' = 6.28) as the most distant object known. In 2003, [[SDF J132418.3+271455]] (''z'' = 6.578) was discovered, and took over the title of most remote object known, most remote galaxy known, and most remote normal galaxy known.
