[[File:John Cuff and his assistant, ca. 1772, Royal Collection by Johan Zoffany.jpg|thumb|right|''John Cuff'', by [[Johan Zoffany]] (1772)<ref name="rct">{{cite web|title=John Cuff|url=https://www.royalcollection.org.uk/collection/404434/john-cuff|publisher=Royal Collection Trust|accessdate=27 February 2017}}</ref>]] '''John Cuff''' (c. 1708 &ndash; c. 1772) was an important English scientific instrument maker, particularly of [[microscope]]s.<ref name=odnb>{{Cite ODNB|id=48225 | title=Cuff, John (1708?–1772?)}}</ref><ref name="musgal"/>
He was apprenticed to the optical instrument maker James Mann.<ref name="smg"/> Cuff eventually set up his own establishment as a "SPECTACLE ''and'' MICROSCOPE ''Maker'', At the sign of the Reflecting MICROSCOPE and SPECTACLES opposite [[Serjeant's Inn]]"<ref name="sspl">{{cite web |url=http://www.ssplprints.com/image/97033/advertisement-for-john-cuff-spectacle-and-microscope-maker-1743 |title=Advertisement for John Cuff, spectacle and microscope maker, 1743. |publisher=[[Science & Society Picture Library]]}}</ref> "(1737-57) & Double Microscope, three Pairs of Golden Spectacles & Hadley's Quadrant opposite Salisbury Court (1757-8) both in Fleet St & Strand, all in London, England."<ref name="smg"/> In 1743, he advertised that he made and sold "Wholesale and Retale, all Manner of curious Optical INSTRUMENTS".<ref name="sspl"/>
Cuff failed to gain membership in the [[Royal Society]],<ref name="jardine"/> but at a Society meeting in the winter of 1738-1739, he encountered [[Johann Nathanael Lieberkühn]], a German physician who was promoting two microscopes of his own invention.<ref name="warner"/> Cuff soon made improvements to the designs.<ref name="warner"/> In 1745, the Swiss naturalist [[Abraham Trembley]] visited London and asked him to design a microscope that would make it easier to observe aquatic creatures as they were moving about.<ref name="warner"/> Two years later, Cuff produced the "AQUATIC MICROSCOPE", "invented by him for the Examination of Water Animals."<ref name="warner"/>
The naturalist [[Henry Baker (naturalist)|Henry Baker]] complained to him about the shortcomings of Baker's Culpeper-type microscope: "Pulling the body of the Instrument up and down was likewise subject to Jerks, which caused a Difficulty in fixing it exactly at the Focus: there was also no good Contrivance for viewing opake Objects".<ref name="jardine"/> Under Baker's direction, Cuff designed and produced an improved "Double Microscope" that quickly supplanted the Culpeper type and became much sought-after not only in England, but all over Europe.<ref name="jardine"/><ref name="golub"/> While superior to other microscopes of the time, optically it was no improvement,<ref>{{cite book|last=Bradbury|first=S.|title=The Microscope Past and Present: Pergamon International Popular Science Series|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1wPLBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA93|date=22 October 2013|publisher=Elsevier|isbn=9781483138978|page=93}}</ref> and like them it still "suffered from severe [[Chromatic aberration|chromatic]] and [[spherical aberration]]."<ref>{{cite web |url=https://micro.magnet.fsu.edu/primer/museum/cuff.html |title=John Cuff's Microscope |author=Michael W. Davidson |publisher=Museum of Microscopy, [[Florida State University]]}}</ref>
Unfortunately, Cuff was apparently not much of a businessman: despite Baker's support, he had to declare bankruptcy in 1750.<ref name="jardine"/> In 1757, a Benjamin Martin opened a competing shop next door to Cuff's establishment on [[Fleet Street]] and drove him out of business the following year.<ref name="jardine"/><ref name="golub"/>
According to the [[Royal Collection Trust]], the German painter [[Johan Zoffany]] was commissioned by King [[George III of the United Kingdom|George III]], a purchaser of Cuff's microscopes, to depict him.<ref name="rct"/> However, doubts have been expressed whether the painting titled ''John Cuff'' actually is a portrayal of him, and it has also been known as ''The Lapidaries'' or ''Two Old Men''.<ref name=odnb /> {{Gallery |title=Instruments by Cuff |align=center |File:The Cuff compound microscope. Wellcome M0017157.jpg|A compound microscope by Cuff, image from the Wellcome Trust |File:Aquatic microscope-MHS 10-P5200273-gradient.jpg|The aquatic microscope made by Cuff for [[Abraham Trembley]], on display at [[Musée d'histoire des sciences de la Ville de Genève]] }}
==Museum holdings== Cuff's instruments are found in several major collections of scientific instruments, including: *[[Science Museum, London]], England: 61 objects<ref name="smg">{{cite web|title=Cuff, John|url=http://collectionsonline.nmsi.ac.uk/detail.php?type=related&kv=52849&t=people|website=Collections Online - People|publisher=Science Museum Group|accessdate=27 February 2017}}</ref> *[[Whipple Museum of the History of Science]], Cambridge, England: five microscopes<ref name="jardine">{{cite web|last1=Jardine|first1=Boris|title=John Cuff and the 'new-constructed' microscope|url=http://www.sites.hps.cam.ac.uk/whipple/explore/microscopes/3microscopemakers/johncuff/|website=Explore Whipple Collections|publisher=Whipple Museum of the History of Science|accessdate=27 February 2017}}</ref> * [[Museo Galileo]], Florence, Italy: two microscopes<ref name="musgal">{{cite web|title=John Cuff|url=http://catalogue.museogalileo.it/biography/JohnCuff.html|website=Virtual Museum|publisher=[[Museo Galileo]]|accessdate=27 February 2017}}</ref> *[[Golub Collection]], [[University of California, Berkeley]], United States: one compound microscope<ref name="golub">{{cite web|title=John Cuff Compound Microscope|url=http://golubcollection.berkeley.edu/18th/18.html|website=The Golub Collection|publisher=University of California at Berkeley|accessdate=27 February 2017}}</ref> *[[National Museum of American History]], Washington D.C., United States: a 1752 aquatic microscope <ref name="warner">{{cite web|last1=Warner|first1=Deborah|title=The oldest microscope in the museum|url=http://americanhistory.si.edu/blog/microscope|website=Smithsonian: National Museum of American History|accessdate=27 February 2017}}</ref> * [[Musée d'histoire des sciences de la Ville de Genève]], Geneva, Switzerland: an aquatic microscope.
