<!-- [[File:undefined|thumbnail|Two twenty-something's disconnecting from reality.]] -->
In [[popular psychology]], a '''quarter-life crisis''' is a [[crisis]] "involving anxiety over the direction and quality of one's life" which is most commonly experienced in a period ranging from a person's twenties up to their mid-thirties<ref>[https://www.collinsdictionary.com/dictionary/english/quarterlife-crisis Quarterlife crisis]. ''Collins English Dictionary''. Retrieved 3 September 2018.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.self.com/wellness/health/2013/03/how-to-survive-quarter-life-crisis/|title=How to Survive a Quarter-Life Crisis|author=Jessica Girdwain|work=SELF}}</ref> (although it can begin as early as 18).<ref name=":0">[https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/quarter-life-crisis-age-most-likely-job-work-relationships-linkedin-career-house-money-a8054616.html The age you're most likely to have a quarter-life crisis]. ''The Independent.'' Author - Rachel Hosie. Published 15 November 2017. Retrieved 3 September 2018.</ref> It is defined by clinical psychologist Alex Fowke as “a period of insecurity, doubt and disappointment surrounding your career, relationships and financial situation".<ref name=":0" />

==Aspects==
According to Merideth Goldstein of ''[[The Boston Globe]]'', the ''quarter-life crisis'' occurs in one's twenties, after entering the "real world" (i.e., after graduating college, and/or after moving out of the family home).<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.boston.com/news/globe/living/articles/2004/09/08/the_quarter_life_crisis |title= The quarter-life crisis |work= [[The Boston Globe]] |first= Meredith |last= Goldstein |date= September 8, 2004 |accessdate= 2007-09-05}}</ref> German psychologist [[Erik H. Erikson]], who proposed eight crises that humans face during their development, proposed the existence of a life crisis occurring at this age. The conflict he associated with young adulthood is the ''Intimacy vs. Isolation'' crisis. According to Erikson after establishing a personal identity in adolescence, young adults seek to form intense, usually [[romantic relationship|romantic]] relationships with other people.<ref>{{cite book |last=Erikson |first=Erik H. |title=Identity: Youth and Crisis |location=New York |publisher=W. W. Norton |year=1968 |isbn= }}</ref>

Common symptoms of a quarter-life crisis are often feelings of being "lost, scared, lonely or confused" about what steps to take in early adulthood. Studies have shown that unemployment and choosing a career path is a major cause for young adults to undergo stress or anxiety. Early stages of one living on their own for the first time and learning to cope without parental help can also induce feelings of isolation and loneliness. Re-evaluation of one's close personal relationships can also be a factor, with sufferers feeling they have outgrown their partner or believing others may be more suitable for them.

Recently, [[millennials]] are sometimes referred to as the ''Boomerang Generation'' or ''Peter Pan Generation'', because of the members' perceived penchant for delaying some rites of passage into adulthood for longer periods than previous generations. These labels were also a reference to a trend toward members returning home after college and/or living with their parents for longer periods than previous generations.<ref>{{cite book |last=Shaputis |first=Kathleen |title=The Crowded Nest Syndrome : Surviving the Return of Adult Children |location=Olympia |publisher=Clutter Fairy |year=2003 |isbn=0972672702 }}</ref> These tendencies might also be partly explained by changes in external social factors rather than characteristics intrinsic to milennials (e.g., higher levels of [[student loan]] debt in the US among milennials when compared to earlier generations can make it more difficult for young adults to achieve traditional markers of independence such as marriage, home ownership or investing).<ref>Tom Anderson. [https://www.nbcnews.com/better/money/debt-locked-student-loans-force-millennials-delay-life-milestones-n404636 Debt-Locked: Student Loans Force Millennials to Delay Life Milestones] NBC News.com, accessed 03 April 2018</ref><ref>Lou Carlozo (May 9, 2016). [https://loans.usnews.com/student-loan-debt-the-invisible-incredible-drain-on-investment Student Loan Debt: The Invisible, Incredible Drain on Investment]. US News & World Report, accessed 03 April 2018</ref>

==In film==
The notion of the quarter-life crisis is explored by the 1967 film ''[[The Graduate]]'', one of the first film depictions of this issue. Other notable films that also do so are ''[[Bright Lights, Big City (film)|Bright Lights, Big City]]''; ''[[The Paper Chase (film)|The Paper Chase]]''; ''[[St. Elmo's Fire (film)|St. Elmo's Fire]]''; ''[[How to Be]]''; ''[[Reality Bites]]''; ''[[Garden State (film)|Garden State]]''; ''[[Accepted (film)|Accepted]]''; ''[[Ghost World (film)|Ghost World]]''; ''[[High Fidelity (film)|High Fidelity]]''; ''[[(500) Days of Summer]]''; ''[[Lost in Translation (film)|Lost in Translation]]''; ''[[Silver Linings Playbook]]''; ''[[Vicky Cristina Barcelona]]''; and ''[[Shaun of the Dead]]''; as well as the musical ''[[Avenue Q]]'', in the television show ''[[The Office (U.S. TV series)|The Office]]'',  and the HBO television series ''[[Girls (TV series)|Girls]]''. The 2008 web series ''[[Quarterlife]]'' was so named for the phenomenon. Other movies exploring the quarter-life crisis include: ''[[Tiny Furniture]]'', ''[[The Puffy Chair]]'', ''[[Fight Club]]'', ''[[Stranger than Fiction (2006 film)|Stranger than Fiction]]'', ''[[Greenberg (film)|Greenberg]]'', ''[[Frances Ha]]'' and ''[[Eternal Sunshine of the Spotless Mind]]''. A 2014 comedy directed by Lynn Shelton titled ''[[Laggies]]'' lightheartedly delves into the complexities of a quarter-life crisis.<ref>https://www.theconfusedmillennial.com/quarter-life-crisis-movies/</ref>

==In music==
The 2003 [[John Mayer]] single "[[Why Georgia]]" explores the concept of a quarter-life crisis. The song was based upon John Mayer's experiences during this age period, when he moved to [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.berklee.edu/bt/172/coverstory.html|title=Berklee Today|publisher=}}</ref>

The 1975 [[Fleetwood Mac]] song "[[Landslide (Fleetwood Mac song)|Landslide]]", written by [[Stevie Nicks]] in her late twenties, explores many of the self-doubts and fears of the quarter-life crisis, at a time when Nicks professed to be uncertain about her musical career and her romantic life.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.songfacts.com/detail.php?id=2083|title=Landslide by Fleetwood Mac Songfacts|publisher=}}</ref>

English indie rock band [[Spector (band)|Spector]]'s song "True Love (For Now)", the opening track to their 2012 album ''[[Enjoy It While It Lasts]]'', references a quarter-life crisis.

"20 Something", the final track on ''[[SZA (singer)|SZA]]''{{'}}s 2017 album [[Ctrl (SZA album)|Ctrl]], delves into the many insecurities she experienced in her twenties, both personal and professional, and the urgency she felt to make the most of her life before entering into mature adulthood.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://genius.com/12132246|title=20 Something, SZA|publisher=Genius Media Group, Inc.}}</ref>

