'''''Shrouds of the Night''''' is a book from the [[astronomy]] genre.

==Overview==
This books is an education on [[dark matter]], the invisible matter which comprises about 70% of space.<ref>{{cite book|author1=David L. Block|author2=Kenneth Freeman|author3=Ivânio Puerari|title=Galaxies and their Masks: A Conference in Honour of K.C. Freeman, FRS|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PK7MoOWD-F8C&pg=PA2|date=12 November 2010|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=978-1-4419-7317-7|page=2}}</ref> The book was written at the [[Mount Stromlo Observatory]] in 2007 by David Block and [[Ken Freeman (astronomer)|Ken Freeman]].  It can be seen as a timetable presenting astronomical photography from 1826 to the present day.<ref>{{cite web|last1=McClurg-Welland|first1=Ian|title=Book Reviews   Shrouds of the Night|url=http://astronomynow.com/books/Shrouds%20of%20the%20Night.html|publisher=Astronomy Now|accessdate=3 January 2018}}</ref>

The reader is exposed to information about galaxies in which challenges and concepts facing the astronomical community today have been explored.

==History==
Much of the content of this book is published here for the first time.  Two examples of this are: one from Arizona's Lowell Observatory and another from the Royal Astronomical Society of London.<ref>{{cite web|title=Shrouds of the Night Masks of the Milky Way and Our Awesome New View of Galaxies|url=https://www.springer.com/gp/book/9780387789743|publisher=Springer|accessdate=3 January 2018}}</ref>

